<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-179-901  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 179 901.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Vision Graphics andamp; Image Processing  July 1990 v51 n1p20(18).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Direct construction of the perspective projection aspect graph ofconvex polyhedra. (technical)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Stewman, John H.; Bowyer, Kevin W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An algorithm to use the boundary surface of convex polyedra todirectly calculate their exact perspective projection aspect graphhas been developed.andP;  There are two major stages to the algorithm.andO;First, an intermediate data structure, called the parcellationgraph, is created.andP;  This structure summarizes totally theparcellation of the viewing space around the object.andP;  Second,another intermediate data structure, called the evaluation matrix,is processed to build identification numbers for the viewing cellswhich exist for a given object.andP;  The process also determines whichcells are linked by visual events.andP;  A perspective projection graphis a more realistic representation than an orthographic projectionaspect graph.andP;  The algorithm is implemented in C and runs on a Sunworkstation.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Sun Microsystems 3-80 (Workstation) (usage).andO;Topic:     Computer VisionGraph TheoryAlgorithmsC Programming Language.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Depiction of the aspect graph of a tetrahedron. (chart)A truncated wedge and its aspect graph. (chart)Plane equations for the truncated wedge. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>